Comparing Classification Accuracy
Ideally, we‚Äôd split the data into training and test sets, compare different classifiers and pick the best. We might even keep a third set of data, the ‚Äòvalidation‚Äô set, to get a better idea of how our chosen classifier will perform on unseen data. As with the different options for input layers, I‚Äôll leave this for a second tutorial. For now, we will be lazy and evaluate the accuracy on the training data: print(‚ÄòAccuuracy‚Äô, trained.confusionMatrix().accuracy());
The accuracy of a CART classifier is listed as 65%. Not bad, given that there are 10 classes, but not great either. Switching to a random forest model gives a much higher accuracy score, but may be subject to overfitting.

Training/Fine-Tuning a model
